From 7ccadbc04af5d12d45bb4fd83fe0f8a40d13eb0e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Yang Jeong Hun <onyxclover9931@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 9 Mar 2026 21:39:43 +0900
Subject: [PATCH] hv_sock: Fix premature -EIO in hvs_stream_has_data()

 * In f0c5827, modified hvs_stream_has_data() to return the exact number of readable bytes.
 * However, it introduced a regression in WSL2 environments where stdin redirection from Windows to Linux
   (e.g., `echo hi | wsl -u root sh`) silently fails and returns error code 1.
 * The issue occurs when the payload of the current packet has been fully drained (hvs->recv_data_len == 0),
   but the descriptor (hvs->recv_desc) has not yet been cleaned up by the recvmsg() path.
 * If the VMBus ring buffer already has the next packet waiting (hvs_channel_readable_payload() == 1),
   the current logic evaluates 'need_refill' as false and incorrectly returns -EIO.
 * This propagates a POLLERR to userspace, prematurely aborting the stream and breaking the pipe.
 * Fix this by returning 1 instead of -EIO in this edge case.
 * Since there is pending data in the ring buffer, returning 1 triggers EPOLLIN, allowing the recvmsg()
   loop to clean up the drained descriptor and properly fetch the next packet.
 * This commit fixes f0c5827.

Test: Build and type `echo echo hi |  wsl -u root sh` in Windows CMD
Signed-off-by: Yang Jeong Hun <onyxclover9931@gmail.com>
---
 net/vmw_vsock/hyperv_transport.c | 8 +++++++-
 1 file changed, 7 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/net/vmw_vsock/hyperv_transport.c b/net/vmw_vsock/hyperv_transport.c
index 432fcbbd14d4..0464e91ac70a 100644
--- a/net/vmw_vsock/hyperv_transport.c
+++ b/net/vmw_vsock/hyperv_transport.c
@@ -703,8 +703,14 @@ static s64 hvs_stream_has_data(struct vsock_sock *vsk)
 	switch (hvs_channel_readable_payload(hvs->chan)) {
 	case 1:
 		need_refill = !hvs->recv_desc;
+		/*
+		 * recv_desc is not null, but recv_data_len is 0.
+		 * The current packet is drained but the ring buffer has more data.
+		 * return 1 to trigger EPOLLIN so recvmsg() can clean up the
+		 * current descriptor and fetch the next packet.
+		 */
 		if (!need_refill)
-			return -EIO;
+			return 1;
 
 		hvs->recv_desc = hv_pkt_iter_first(hvs->chan);
 		if (!hvs->recv_desc)
-- 
2.53.0

